# Git Workflow & Conventions

## Commit Message Format

### Conventional Commits
```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

### Types
- `feat:` - New feature
- `fix:` - Bug fix
- `docs:` - Documentation only
- `style:` - Code style (formatting, semicolons)
- `refactor:` - Code refactoring (no feature/fix)
- `perf:` - Performance improvement
- `test:` - Adding/updating tests
- `build:` - Build system or dependencies
- `ci:` - CI/CD configuration
- `chore:` - Maintenance tasks

### Scopes
- `mobile` - Mobile app changes
- `backend` - Backend changes
- `wallet` - Wallet functionality
- `auth` - Authentication
- `tx` - Transactions
- `crosschain` - Cross-chain features
- `ui` - UI components
- `api` - API endpoints

### Examples
```bash
# Feature
feat(wallet): add multi-chain balance aggregation

# Bug fix
fix(tx): handle timeout in cross-chain status polling

# With ticket reference
feat(crosschain): implement LiFi router execution [EY-123]

# Breaking change
feat(api)!: change transaction response format

BREAKING CHANGE: Transaction amount now returns string instead of number
```

### Rules
- Subject line max 72 characters
- Use imperative mood: "add" not "added" or "adds"
- No period at end of subject
- Separate subject from body with blank line
- Reference issues/tickets in footer

## Branch Naming

### Format
```
<type>/<ticket>-<short-description>
```

### Examples
```bash
feature/EY-123-crosschain-lifi-integration
fix/EY-456-balance-refresh-bug
refactor/EY-789-wallet-service-cleanup
hotfix/EY-999-critical-security-patch
```

### Types
- `feature/` - New features
- `fix/` - Bug fixes
- `refactor/` - Code refactoring
- `hotfix/` - Critical production fixes
- `docs/` - Documentation updates
- `test/` - Test additions/updates

## Branching Strategy

### Main Branches
- `main` - Production-ready code
- `develop` - Integration branch for features

### Workflow
```
main ←─── release ←─── develop ←─── feature/*
  ↑                        ↑
  └── hotfix/* ────────────┘
```

1. Create feature branch from `develop`
2. Develop and commit with conventional commits
3. Create PR to `develop`
4. After review and CI pass, merge
5. Periodically merge `develop` → `main` for releases

## Pull Request Guidelines

### PR Title
Same format as commit messages:
```
feat(wallet): add balance refresh functionality [EY-123]
```

### PR Description Template
```markdown
## Summary
Brief description of changes

## Changes
- Added X
- Fixed Y
- Updated Z

## Testing
- [ ] Unit tests added/updated
- [ ] Manual testing completed
- [ ] E2E tests pass

## Screenshots (if UI changes)
[Add screenshots]

## Related Issues
Closes #123
```

### Review Checklist
- [ ] Code follows project conventions
- [ ] Tests cover new functionality
- [ ] No console.logs or debug code
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets
- [ ] Error handling is appropriate
- [ ] Documentation updated if needed

## Pre-Commit Checks
```bash
# Run before committing
npm run lint
npm run type-check
npm test

# Or use husky hooks (auto-run)
```

## Rebase vs Merge
- **Feature branches**: Rebase onto `develop` before merge
- **PRs**: Squash and merge preferred
- **Release**: Merge commit to preserve history

```bash
# Update feature branch
git checkout feature/my-feature
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/develop

# If conflicts, resolve then:
git rebase --continue
```
